Dependence of p53-TAD Secondary Structure on
Force Field. The level of secondary structure of IDPs is often ﬁnely tuned by their sequences, which is critical for signaling ﬁdelity.8 Many disease mutations in IDPs have been predicted
to alter secondary structure with higher probabilities than functionally neutral mutations,15 which may perturb the
protein interaction network and lead to misregulation. Multiple partial helices have also been identiﬁed in p53-TAD70,75 and suggested to play roles in mediating p53’s interactions with key regulators including MDM2 and CBP/p300.56 Cancer-
associated p53-TAD mutant K24N has been shown to reduce the helicity of residues 18−27.75 Therefore, it is very important to evaluate how well current force ﬁelds can capture residual
secondary structures. Like chain dimension, the secondary
structure content of p53-TAD also depends strongly on the chosen force ﬁeld. The helical content in c22* simulations,
although not fully converged for certain residues, seemed to be the highest among these four force ﬁelds, where three

segments (residues 15−25, 35−45, and 45−55) constantly
showed helical propensity of at least 40% for both control and
folding simulations (Figure 2). In contrast, there was almost no
residual helical structure in both control and folding simulations using the ﬀ99SB-ILDN-TIP4P-D force ﬁeld
(Figure 2). The residual helicities for the other two force ﬁelds, ﬀ99SB-ILDN and a99SB-disp, were in between these
two extremes. Previous NMR studies have shown that residues 17−29 were ∼10% helical, and two turns were assigned to the regions of 40−44 and 48−52.70,75 Nonetheless, continual sequential dNN NOEs and negative secondary Hα chemical shifts were found in the latter two regions,70 implying that
partial helical elements may exist. Results from the a99SB-disp force ﬁeld appear the most consistent with these experimental
observations (see Figure 2). To better quantify the level of agreement of simulated
ensembles with NMR results we calculated the secondary chemical shifts of Cα and C′ atoms, which are sensitive to the

