secondary structure. The proﬁles of secondary chemical shift
are shown in Figures 5 and 6, and quantitative comparison
between simulated and experimental results is summarized in
Table 3. These results demonstrate that secondary chemical shifts of Cα and C′ atoms from a99SB-disp simulations agreed
the best with experimental measurements, suggesting that this force ﬁeld could properly describe the secondary structure
propensity of p53-TAD. Note that SHIFTX2 could predict
chemical shifts for folded proteins with RMS errors of 0.4412 and 0.5330 ppm for Cα and C′ atoms, respectively.90 Therefore, according to Table 3, results from the ﬀ99SBILDN force ﬁeld also seem in reasonable agreement with
experimental values. In contrast, the content of helical structure is signiﬁcantly underestimated by ﬀ99SB-ILDNTIP4P-D and overestimated by c22* (Figures 5 and 6).
We note a curious observation regarding the propensity of forming 310 helices from multiple fore ﬁelds. As summarized in Figure S9, the 310 helical content in simulations using three CHARMM force ﬁelds was low and signiﬁcantly lower than the corresponding α-helical content (Figure 2). This can be
directly attributed to the CMAP term used in CHARMM force ﬁelds, which was designed to rebalance the propensities of forming α, 310, and π helices.77 In contrast, the Amber family of force ﬁelds appears to generate signiﬁcant 310 helices. The only exception was ﬀ99SB-ILDN-TIP4P-D, but this may be a
direct result of increased water dispersion in the TIP4P-D water force ﬁeld that destabilizes both α (e.g., Figure 2) and
310 helices. As shown in Figure S9, the 310 helical propensity is comparable to the α-helical content for residues 20−25 in both ﬀ99SB-ILDN and a99SB-disp simulations. Similar observations have also been reported previously for ﬀ99SB*-ILDN,42,48,49 a force ﬁeld modiﬁed from ﬀ99SB-ILDN by rebalancing the

backbone helix−coil propensity, where the probability of forming 310 helix is higher in ﬀ99SB*-ILDN simulations than in those using other force ﬁelds (see Figure 2 in ref 50). It is
known that 310-helix represents the third principal secondary structure in folded proteins, following the α-helix and βsheet,102 with a population of ∼3%.103 Nevertheless, the
population of 310-helix in IDPs remains unclear. To better assess if there is any systematic bias in simulating p53-TAD or other IDPs using these force ﬁelds, more experimental data are
needed, including three-bond coupling constants. Detection of Transient Long-Range Contact Forma-
tion Using Diﬀerent Force Fields. Transient long-range
interactions in IDPs are known to have important functional implications.104−106 For example, a previous NMR study has shown that loss of transient long-range interactions in αsynuclein, an IDP associated with Parkinson’s disease, could
lead to completely unfolded conformations that aggregate more rapidly.106 Such transient long-range interactions have also been found in p53-TAD,74,76 and they can be modulated
both locally and remotely by binding of regulatory proteins or post-translational modiﬁcation.74 Thus, in order to obtain
reliable simulated structural ensembles of p53-TAD, the force ﬁeld also needs to be able to capture such important structural features. Experimentally, PRE in combination with site-speciﬁc
spin labeling provides a powerful tool in detecting transient long-range contact formation for IDPs.76,107−109 The increase in relaxation rate of a proton is proportional to 1/r6, where r is
the distance between the proton and the unpaired electron in a spin label. Because of this 1/r6 dependence, the PRE eﬀect is
suitable for identifying transient long-range contacts and insensitive to conformations with large proton−electron
distance. Since PRE measurement could detect contact

